Writing to silver — save modes, partitioning, and idempotency.

This is the last step of every transformation: taking your cleaned, conformed result and landing it in a governed silver table. There are two write patterns the exam tests, and one idea that runs through both.

The first is full overwrite. Here the silver build is idempotent by design — re-running it rebuilds the table from bronze, so if a job fails halfway and you retry, you're safe. You write with mode "overwrite", and you add overwrite-schema true only when the schema has actually changed. And while we're here, know the save modes: append adds rows, overwrite replaces the table, error — which is the default, also called error-if-exists — fails if the table already exists, and ignore quietly does nothing if it exists.

The second pattern is upsert with merge-into. Instead of a full rebuild, silver tracks incremental updates coming from bronze change-data-capture. You merge on the natural key — transaction-i-d — and when a row matches you update it, when it doesn't you insert it.

Then there are layout decisions. For new tables, reach for Liquid Clustering on your natural query keys — cluster-by customer-i-d and transaction-at — which we covered in module two. It replaces both partition-by and Z-ORDER. Legacy tables may still use partition-by on a date column, but don't reach for that on anything new. And enable Predictive Optimization at the catalog level so silver stays compact without you scheduling a manual optimise job — that's module eight.

And the throughline is idempotency. A full-overwrite rebuild is safe to retry. A merge keyed on the natural key is safe to re-apply. Either way, re-running the job converges to exactly the same silver — and that safety is what makes a pipeline trustworthy.
